The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Friday, August 27, 2004  The City Diary
																																																		Warming up again to the water transport project, the Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee government announced on Thursday that the Kestopur, Bagjola and New Cut canals would be made navigable to reduce the congestion on the roads in Chitpur, Beleghata and Maniktala. In the first phase of the project, the Kestopur canal will be made navigable and launches will ply between Rajarhat and Chitpur. In the next phase, Rajarhat will be connected to Kulti, in North 24-Parganas.																																																								he chief minister discussed the project at a meeting with municipal affairs minister Asok Bhattacharya, public health engineering minister Goutam Deb, irrigation minister Ganesh Mondol, transport minister Subhas Chakraborty and mayor Subrata Mukherjee. With a railway terminal coming up at Chitpur shortly, the adjoining areas are likely to get more congested. Were convinced that the canal navigation project is feasible, minister Bhattacharya said. 																																																		Mohammed Pappu, 18, fell off a running bus on route 214 and was crushed under its wheels in Kamarhati on Thursday morning. He died on the spot. Police said Pappu, standing on the footboard, had an altercation with one of the conductors, and the latter, in a fit of rage, pushed him. Both the conductors fled after the incident. The driver was handed over to the police.																																																		Transport minister Subhas Chakraborty said on Thursday that he had written to Union finance minister P. Chidambaram, asking him to review the 10 per cent service tax announced in the Union budget. 																																																		CESC cash offices at Chowringhee Square, Howrah, Kamarhati, Mandeville Gardens, Shyambazar and Taratala will stay open for a longer duration on Saturdays. The offices will open at 8 am and close at 2 pm.																																																		A green bench of Calcutta High Court on Thursday directed the Calcutta Improvement Trust (CIT) to file a report, detailing measures it had taken to clean up Rabindra Sarobar. Justice Barin Ghosh and Justice A.K. Basu stressed the need for taking all possible steps to develop the lake. 																																																		Calcutta High Court on Thursday allowed the bail plea of Dwijadas Banerjee, former Visva-Bharati registrar, who was arrested in connection with the theft of a Japanese manuscript. The sleuths have failed to nail him. 																																																		The contempt case against Left Front chairman Biman Bose for criticising Justice Amitava Lala, following the imposition of curbs on rallies, came up for hearing in Calcutta High Court on Thursday. Boses counsel claimed his clients disputed statements were not contemptuous.																																																		Police on Thursday rescued a Nepalese girl from Jagaddal, in North 24-Parganas. The 19-year-old had left home a few days ago without informing her parents. 																																																		A group of serving and retired teachers of some state universities on Thursday urged the government not to oppose the bail pleas of Dilip Sinha and Dilip Mukhopadhyay, former vice-chancellor and registrar of Visva-Bharati. Both were arrested in connection with a marksheet scandal. To Allahabad Bank Officers Association for constructing a school building for orphans at Jogindrapur 
